   164	## 2. Timers
   165	
   166	### 2.1 `t_lease` — `1.0 s` (lease liveness, G4)
   167	
   168	**Derivation.** `t_lease` bounds the age of the last *produced* solution frame (companion/
   169	estimator liveness), and `SAFETY_CASE.md` §1.1/§3.1 requires `t_lease < GPS_TIMEOUT_MS`
   170	(4000 ms). Frames renew at the DR-fill cadence (every accepted IMU propagation, ~10 ms at the
   171	100 Hz nominal, CONTRACTS v5.1) with the nav solution nominal at 5 Hz (200 ms). D17a
   172	(`tools/sitl/evidence/D17a.md`) measures native ArduPilot fix-type degradation at ~1.0 s and
   173	EKF-failsafe HOLD at ~5.07 s. Proposed **1.0 s**. Margin basis, stated against the correct
   174	cadence: the *implemented* renewal opportunity is the **DR-fill epoch emitted on every accepted
   175	IMU propagation — nominally ~10 ms at the 100 Hz IMU rate (CONTRACTS v5.1)**, so 1.0 s is
   176	**~100×** the renewal cadence; the 5 Hz nominal navigation *publication* period (200 ms) is the
   177	coarser cadence and 1.0 s is 5× that. Either way, 1.0 s comfortably absorbs scheduler/GC jitter
   178	and sparse-frame intervals. It is 4× below `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` (4 s) and ~5× below the ~5.07 s
   179	native failsafe — so in **Case A** (companion alive) the supervisor self-revokes well before
   180	ArduPilot's own reaction. Note the guarantee is Case-A-only: `t_lease`
   181	does nothing in Case B (companion death/link loss), where only the physical layer is credited
   182	(`SAFETY_CASE.md` §2.1).
   183	
   184	**Sensitivity.** 2× tight (0.5 s): nuisance lease expiry on a normal scheduling stall or GC
   185	pause → spurious revocations. 2× loose (2.0 s): still < 4 s, but the Case-A self-revoke lead
   186	over the ~5.07 s native failsafe shrinks from ~4 s to ~3 s, and a frozen-but-alive estimator
   187	(H4) keeps asserting authority up to 2 s longer.
   188	
   189	**Validation plan.** SITL/HIL timing of the Case-A hand-to-helm path at pinned Rover-4.6.3
   190	(measured companion-commanded HOLD latency is ~51 ms, D17a) to confirm the self-revoke
   190	(measured companion-commanded HOLD latency is ~51 ms, D17a) to confirm the self-revoke
   191	completes with margin; replay of estimator-stall (H4) injections to confirm the lease expires
   192	on a frozen sequence; on-target scheduler-jitter measurement to confirm 1.0 s clears the
   193	worst-case frame gap.
   194	
   195	### 2.2 `t_dr` — `120 s` (dead-reckoning authority, G2d)
   196	
   197	**Derivation.** `t_dr` bounds the age of the last *absolute* (LEO/aided) position-constraining
   198	observation and revokes authority even if the covariance still looks in-limit (H1 backstop,
   199	independent of the possibly-optimistic covariance of H2). During all-LEO-loss, DR frames keep
   200	renewing the lease (G4) and authority ends on G2 — the growing PL **or** `t_dr`, whichever
   201	first (`SAFETY_CASE.md` §1.1/§2.3). Proposed **120 s**: long enough to ride through realistic
   202	multi-satellite handover gaps (tens of seconds of no valid correlation), short enough that an
   203	optimistic covariance cannot let a badly-drifted DR solution retain authority. At a
   204	conservative post-loss residual velocity-error scale of ~0.05 m/s, 120 s of pure DR is ~6 m of
   205	velocity-driven drift — well inside the 100 m denied PL — so under a *correct* covariance the
   206	PL check remains the primary bound and `t_dr` is the backstop against an *incorrect* one.
   207	**This is the weakest-evidence timer in the set**: no replayed LEO-gap statistics exist yet, so
   208	120 s is a displacement-hull engineering estimate.
   209	
   210	**Sensitivity.** 2× tight (60 s): may nuisance-revoke during normal sparse-fix gaps in weak
   211	geometry, costing availability. 2× loose (240 s): admits ~12 m+ of unmonitored velocity-driven
   212	drift and, more importantly, doubles the window in which an optimistic covariance (H2) can hold
   213	authority on a stale solution — the exact hazard `t_dr` exists to bound.
   214	
   215	**Validation plan.** GNSS-withheld replay of minutes-long LEO gaps (the test `SAFETY_CASE.md`
   216	§1.1 explicitly names): measure real revisit-gap statistics for the operating area/constellation
   217	mix, and the DR position-error growth vs truth across a gap, then set `t_dr` to the largest gap
   218	the drift budget tolerates inside the denied PL. Re-derive for any non-displacement hull.
   219	
   220	### 2.3 `t_eph` — `21600 s` (6 h ephemeris-age gate, G2e)
   221	
   222	**Derivation.** Directly from the baseline: SupGP maximum age provisional **6 hours**, anchored
   223	to the first supplied error-growth datum (~0.94 km orbit error at 6 h). The baseline states the
   224	orbit-error → navigation-integrity mapping is `[UNVERIFIED]` and the limit "shall be validated
   225	or tightened before steering trials." Proposed **21600 s**, matching the baseline unchanged.
   226	
   227	**Sensitivity.** 2× loose (12 h): SupGP orbit error grows to several km → range-rate prediction
   228	bias that the pass-nuisance state may not fully absorb → biased Doppler entering fusion. 2×
   229	tight (3 h): forces more frequent ephemeris refresh; if the at-sea fetch path is intermittent,
   230	over-age exclusion of otherwise-healthy satellites thins geometry and hurts availability.
   231	
   232	**Validation plan.** Propagate SupGP vs precise/near-real-time ephemerides to quantify the
   233	orbit-error → predicted-range-rate-error → navigation-integrity chain; tighten 6 h to the age
   234	at which predicted-range-rate error reaches the tracker/EKF residual budget. Confirm the at-sea
   235	ephemeris-refresh cadence supports the chosen age.
   236	
   237	### 2.4 Per-source freshness deadlines — and a fail-closed enforcement gap
   238	
   239	**Why this section exists (fixes the review HIGH finding).** The `SAFETY_CASE.md` fail-closed
   240	register (§1.1 timer table, §1.2 sub-predicates, §5) names **per-source freshness deadlines**
   241	— "last IMU / magnetometer / speed-log / ephemeris sample" — as authority-contract parameters
   242	feeding G2/G3, and §1's fail-closed gate covers "per-source freshness limits" by name. **These
   243	deadlines are absent from `AuthorityParams` (CONTRACTS v5) and from `AuthorityParams::is_complete()`.**
   244	The consequence is a real enforcement gap: **a fully-populated `AuthorityParams` satisfies
   245	`is_complete()` while the per-source freshness limits named in the safety-case register remain
   246	unfrozen** — so the code-level fail-closed gate does *not* cover the whole safety-case register.
   247	This section proposes values *and* registers the gap (§5.4) as a contracts-owner action item;
   248	it is **not** silently absorbed into the appendix as though the fields existed.
   249	
   250	The per-source deadlines are derived from the rate contract (`DESIGN_BASELINE.md`/CONTRACTS v2
   251	Rate contract) as a small multiple of each source's nominal period, sized to the fault each
   252	staleness represents:
   253	
   254	| Source | Nominal rate | Proposed deadline | Derivation / fault represented |
   255	|---|---|---|---|
   256	| IMU | 100 Hz (10 ms) | **0.10 s** | ~10 nominal periods. IMU drives *every* propagation; staleness makes time-propagation untrustworthy → the baseline's "IMU stream stale ⇒ revoke" row. Tightest deadline; must be ≪ `t_lease` (1.0 s) since IMU staleness is a more immediate fault than mere output silence. |
   257	| Magnetometer (each) | 10 Hz (100 ms) | **0.50 s** | ~5 nominal periods, per magnetometer. Loss of one → continue on the other (baseline); loss of both → heading PL (G2h) revokes. Looser than IMU because heading degradation is caught by G2h. |
   258	| Speed log | 5 Hz (200 ms) | **1.00 s** | ~5 nominal periods. Speed-log loss removes only current/ground-speed separation (baseline); G2 catches downstream effects. Least safety-critical of the three marine feeds. |
   259	| Ephemeris | event / cache | **= `t_eph` (21600 s)** | The ephemeris "sample" is the SupGP record whose age gate **is** `t_eph` (§2.3). A separate short freshness deadline would be redundant; the age gate governs. Stated to avoid a duplicate parameter. |
   260	
   261	**Sensitivity.** IMU 2× tight (0.05 s): nuisance revoke on scheduler jitter/USB hiccup. IMU 2×
   262	loose (0.20 s): up to 0.2 s of propagation on a stale IMU before revoke — the exact
   263	untrustworthy-propagation hazard the deadline exists to bound. Magnetometer/speed-log looser
   264	deadlines trade heading/current availability against staleness; their downstream effects are
   265	also caught by G2, so they are secondary to IMU.
   266	
   267	**Validation plan.** On-target bus-jitter and gap measurement per source (the deadline must
   268	clear the worst-case healthy inter-sample gap with margin); withheld replay of single-source
   269	dropout injections confirming revoke fires at the deadline and the estimator keeps running
   270	(baseline: staleness stops authority, never the estimator); IMU-stale injection tied to the
   271	`SAFETY_CASE.md` §2.3 degradation row.
   272	
   273	**Registered gap (see §5.4).** Until CONTRACTS adds these fields to `AuthorityParams` and
   274	`is_complete()`, freezing them cannot be enforced by the code-level fail-closed gate; they must
   275	be enforced upstream (executive/integrity ingress) and their freeze tracked separately.
